				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Q. and A.: James E. Garvey on Chinese Solutions for America&#8217;s Carp Problem</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Austin Ramzy			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-13T22:03:44+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 13, 2014 6:03 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 13, 2014 6:03 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/25/world/25sino-carp01/25sino-carp01-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/25/world/25sino-carp01/25sino-carp01-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/25/world/25sino-carp01/25sino-carp01-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003137274" width="592" height="364" alt="Silver carp jumping out of the water after being disturbed by the sound of watercraft on the Illinois River."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="364"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Silver carp jumping out of the water after being disturbed by the sound of watercraft on the Illinois River.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Nerissa Michaels/Illinois River Biological Station, via Detroit Free Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/13/q-and-a-james-e-garvey-on-chinese-solutions-for-americas-carp-problem/" data-title="Q. and A.: James E. Garvey on Chinese Solutions for America&#8217;s Carp Problem" data-description="The American researcher recently visited China to learn from its experience with Asian carp, a fish considered a pest in the United States but considered an important source of food, as well as a cultural symbol, in China.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">China loves carp. The United States, not so much. The fish is widely found on dinner tables across East and Southeast AsiaÂ  but largely ignored by consumers in North America. Instead, invasive Asian carp species are considered a pest in United States waterways and a threat to those in Canada as well.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP2/26sino-CARP2-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP2/26sino-CARP2-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP2/26sino-CARP2-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003140063" width="190" height="266" alt="James E. Garvey, vice chancellor for research, Southern Illinois University, Carbondale."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="266"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">James E. Garvey, vice chancellor for research, Southern Illinois University, Carbondale.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of James E. Garvey</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.zoology.siu.edu/faculty-staff/faculty/current-faculty/garvey-j.php">James E. Garvey</a>, vice chancellor for research at Southern Illinois University, Carbondale, recently visited China as part of a project researching the Yangtze and Mississippi rivers, including a look at the Asian carp present in both. In an interview, he discussed how Asian carp became such a headache in the United States, what can be learned from China&#8217;s long experience with the fish and whether there&#8217;s hope for eating away the problem:</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>When did Asian carp begin to be an issue in the United States, and how widespread are the fish now?</strong><br />
<span id="more-19472"></span></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are several species of Asian carp in the U.S. The Asian carp I refer to here are bighead and silver carp, two species that were introduced into the U.S. in 1973 to &#8220;clean&#8221; water in ponds. The U.S. had just passed the Clean Water Act, and biologists were looking for ways to improve water quality without the use of chemicals. These two species eat bacteria, algae and small zooplankton, all of which take up nutrient pollution. So the idea was that these Asian carp species would consume these organisms and rapidly incorporate the nutrient waste into their flesh. Because Asian carp are high in protein, they could then be used as food. This seemed like a win-win at the time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Biologists found that Asian carp did not improve water quality as promised. But by then â as early as 1974 â the fish had escaped into the wild from ponds in Arkansas. Bighead and silver carp were discovered to be reproducing in the Mississippi River drainage by the early 1990s. There was some mild interest from the public and resource managers for the first 30 years of the invasion, but little funding was available for research and control.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the early 2000s, Asian carp were found in the Illinois River, which directly connects to the Great Lakes via a canal system in Chicago. This spurred concern because the Great Lakes fishery is valued at more than $7 billion annually. If Asian carp moved into the Great Lakes, then this valuable fishery might collapse. At the same time, Asian carp have been moving up the Ohio River toward the eastern U.S. states and up the Mississippi River toward Minnesota, a state whose economy depends on its thousands of lakes and streams. Basically, Asian carp moved far enough north to threaten valuable fisheries, which caused the U.S. federal and state governments to take action, with added pressure from the Canadian government, which does not want our Asian carp problem becoming a Canadian problem.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Asian carp are distributed throughout most of the central U.S. After the dramatic floods that occurred in the Mississippi River in 2011, Asian carp greatly expanded their range into inland lakes and small streams. Several research studies have shown that Asian carp are capable of spreading through most of North America if their invasion is left unchecked.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What problems do Asian carp cause in the United States?<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We are still learning about the problems. One of the reasons we know so little is because large rivers in the U.S. are terribly understudied. When Asian carp invaded the Illinois River over 15 years ago, we were lucky enough to have some pre-carp invasion data collected by a federally funded river-monitoring project. These data show that the Illinois River ecosystem changed after Asian carp invaded, with some negative effects on native fishes. With most invasions, native species go extinct. To date, we have not seen any native U.S. fish species go extinct due to the invasion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Asian carp move. These fish evolved in the swift-flowing Yangtze River, and our research on Asian carp movement in the U.S. shows that they move tremendous distances â hundreds of kilometers â when river discharge is high, i.e., during flooding. They seem to be designed to disperse when water is raging. This also happens to be the time when water bodies are connected by floods, allowing these fish to &#8220;jump&#8221; from one watershed to another with ease. Our research shows that dams pose little barrier to movement for Asian carp as compared to native fishes.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How exactly do the Asian carp harm native fish populations?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We think it is due to competition for food. It also may be displacement. Carp congregate in huge schools and may literally push natives out of their preferred habitat.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What has been tried to control their spread?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the early 2000s, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers built an electric barrier across the Illinois River below the canal system in Chicago. This barrier sends an electrical current to prevent invasive fish, with a focus on Asian carp, from moving between the Great Lakes and the Illinois River. The barrier has been expanded in the past few years, and now includes three electrical fields. No Asian carp have been found to have moved through the barrier to date. The cost of the barrier and its operation is in the range of $15 million to $20 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the past four years, Illinois has contracted with fishers to physically remove Asian carp from areas near the Chicago waterway system below the electrical barrier. They have removed more than one million pounds of carp from this location, an area where the carp population is considered &#8220;sparse.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are many other techniques being explored including using food with poisons that only can be digested by Asian carp. Fish attractants to lure Asian carp into nets. And so on.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The most parsimonious solution, in my view, is massive harvest. However, the federal and state governments are hesitant to provide subsidies for fishing as a control option, unless the fishing takes place near the edge of the range of the population, where arguably fishing has the least impact on the population. There is a fear that government support of fishing will create economic dependence on the very species we are trying to eliminate. And this fear might be merited.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Describe your visit to China, and what you hoped to learn.<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This was my second visit hosted by the Nature Conservancy&#8217;s Great Rivers Partnership between the Yangtze River and the Mississippi River. These two rivers have many similarities, including the presence of Asian carp. China has been studying and culturing Asian carp for thousands of years, and their scientists, resource managers and fishermen have a wealth of knowledge that needs to be tapped. This was realized several years ago by a colleague of mine, Duane Chapman with the U.S. Geological Survey, and I am trying to follow in his footsteps to learn as much as I can from my friends and colleagues in China. The primary goal of the exchange was for the two countries to agree to exchange information and share researchers and students.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What sort of reactions do you get from people in China when you describe the carp problem in the U.S.?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Obviously, Asian carp are culturally important in China. In Taiyuan, I had the opportunity to visit their cultural heritage museum and see pottery adorned with carp images dating back thousands of years. Carp are good luck and fun to eat. The primary reaction I get from Chinese is, why don&#8217;t we in the U.S. eat the carp? My answer is simple: Americans don&#8217;t eat much fish. And when they do, it&#8217;s not Asian carp but more likely something cultured in another country and imported into the U.S. The economics and logic don&#8217;t make sense to me.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP1/26sino-CARP1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP1/26sino-CARP1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/26/world/26sino-CARP1/26sino-CARP1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003140065" width="480" height="320" alt="A worker at a fish farm in Fuqing, Fujian Province, feeding carp, popular culinary fare in China."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A worker at a fish farm in Fuqing, Fujian Province, feeding carp, popular culinary fare in China.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Chang W. Lee/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Carp are hugely popular in China. How much potential is there for U.S. exports?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Interest in exporting Asian carp to China is huge. However, the interest wanes when the economic realities set in. Catching Asian carp, processing them and getting them to markets in China is more expensive than what the typical Chinese consumer is willing to pay, even for &#8220;wild caught&#8221; Asian carp from the U.S. Asian carp from U.S. waters are low in contaminants, high in protein and &#8220;good&#8221; fats. The problem is conveying that reality to the discriminating Chinese consumer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Obviously, there are worries about competition with aquaculture producers of Asian carp in China. Asian carp imported into China from the U.S. might put a dent in those operations, which is a potential obstacle.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>One issue, it seems, would be the development of commercial carp fishing in the U.S. How widespread is that now? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Inland commercial fishing in the U.S. is a complicated business. Commercial fishing is limited to interstate rivers and the Great Lakes. Fishing in individual states is restricted due to the Lacey Act, which prohibits interstate sales of wild-caught game, including fish.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The inland fishing community in the U.S. is so small and the extent of the Asian carp invasion so broad, that there is huge potential for the growth of carp fishing. The problem is that most people are unwilling to start fishing for carp unless they are assured that they will make a living and be able to pay for their investment.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How about selling Americans on carp?<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most Americans rarely eat fish. So, convincing them to eat Asian carp is going to be an uphill battle. However, there is hope. There are many uses for Asian carp including fish meal, which sells for at least at $1,000 a ton, collagen production, organic fertilizer, fish oil, biodiesel, as well as food. There is big demand for heads in China â makes delicious soup. So, one option is to lop off the heads, which are cheaper to ship, and sell those at a top price in China, and use the rest of the body to generate other products domestically.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another huge market in the U.S. and Canada is the expat Asian communities. We have several buyers in Asian markets throughout the U.S. that take Asian carp. One sticky point is that the Asian communities prefer to have their fish live in market. Current rules in the U.S. and Canada prohibit the live transport of Asian carp, which reduces demand in these markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Researchers at Southern Illinois University did a survey of potential consumers of Asian carp in the U.S. and found that there is broad interest in purchasing these fish among those few Americans who eat fish regularly. We just need to get Americans to eat fish, like the rest of humanity does.</p>
	</div>
